# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: few-shot-learning
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] During SSL, the model learns in two steps.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] First, the task is solved based on an auxiliary or pretext classification task using pseudo-labels, which help to initialize the model parameters.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] Next, the actual task is performed with supervised or unsupervised learning.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] Self-supervised learning has produced promising results in recent years, and has found practical application in fields such as audio processing, and is being used by Facebook and others for speech recognition.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] Pseudo-labels are automatically generated labels that a model assigns to unlabeled data based on its own predictions.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] They are widely used in self-supervised and semi-supervised learning, where ground-truth annotations are limited or unavailable.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] By treating predicted labels as surrogate ground truth, learning algorithms can make use of large quantities of unlabeled data in the training process.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] Pseudo-labeling also plays an important role in systems that must adapt to concept drift, where the statistical properties of the data change over time.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] In these scenarios, the model may detect that an incoming instance deviates from previously learned behavior.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] The system then generates a classification result for that instance, and this predicted class is used as a pseudo-label for updating or retraining model components that are becoming outdated.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] This approach enables continuous adaptation in dynamic environments without requiring manual annotation.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] In many adaptive learning pipelines, pseudo-labels are chosen when the classifier produces sufficiently confident predictions, reducing the risk of propagating errors.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] These pseudo-labeled instances are then incorporated into training to refresh or evolve the model's understanding of emerging data patterns, particularly when existing components show signs of “aging” due to drift or distributional shifts.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] This strategy reduces reliance on manual labeling while helping maintain long-term model performance.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] Autoassociative self-supervised learning is a specific category of self-supervised learning where a neural network is trained to reproduce or reconstruct its own input data.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] In other words, the model is tasked with learning a representation of the data that captures its essential features or structure, allowing it to regenerate the original input.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] The term "autoassociative" comes from the fact that the model is essentially associating the input data with itself.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] This is often achieved using autoencoders, which are a type of neural network architecture used for representation learning.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] Autoencoders consist of an *encoder* network that maps the input data to a lower-dimensional representation (latent space), and a *decoder* network that reconstructs the input from this representation.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] The training process involves presenting the model with input data and requiring it to reconstruct the same data as closely as possible.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] The loss function used during training typically penalizes the difference between the original input and the reconstructed output (e.g. mean squared error).
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] By minimizing this reconstruction error, the autoencoder learns a meaningful representation of the data in its latent space.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] For a binary classification task, training data can be divided into positive examples and negative examples.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] Positive examples are those that match the target.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] For example, if training a classifier to identify birds, the positive training data would include images that contain birds.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] Negative examples would be images that do not.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] Contrastive self-supervised learning uses both positive and negative examples.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] The loss function in contrastive learning is used to minimize the distance between positive sample pairs, while maximizing the distance between negative sample pairs.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] An early example uses a pair of 1-dimensional convolutional neural networks to process a pair of images and maximize their agreement.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] Contrastive Language-Image Pre-training (CLIP) allows joint pretraining of a text encoder and an image encoder, such that a matching image-text pair have image encoding vector and text encoding vector that span a small angle (having a large cosine similarity).
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] InfoNCE (Noise-Contrastive Estimation) is a method to optimize two models jointly, based on Noise Contrastive Estimation (NCE).
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] Non-contrastive self-supervised learning (NCSSL) uses only positive examples.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] Counterintuitively, NCSSL converges on a useful local minimum rather than reaching a trivial solution, with zero loss.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] For the example of binary classification, it would trivially learn to classify each example as positive.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] Effective NCSSL requires an extra predictor on the online side that does not back-propagate on the target side.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] A major class of self-supervised learning moves beyond contrastive pairs, instead maximizing the agreement between views while preventing collapse through statistical constraints.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] Rooted in Deep Canonical Correlation Analysis (Deep CCA), this approach includes Joint-Embedding Architectures (JEA) like Barlow Twins and VICReg, which enforce covariance constraints to learn invariant representations without negative sampling.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] Deep Latent Variable Path Modelling (DLVPM) generalizes this to multimodal systems, using path models to enforce correlation and orthogonality across diverse data types.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] In 2022 Yann LeCun introduced Joint-Embedding Predictive Architectures (JEPA) as a step towards decision making, reasoning, and autonomous human intelligence in machines, including self-improvement through autonomous learning.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] Founded in representation learning, LeCun included the concept of a “world model” in JEPA which aims to enable machines to replicate human intellect by providing machines with a concept for the world in which they exist.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] Unlike autoencoders, JEPAs operate entirely in latent space, avoiding pixel-level noise to focus on semantic structure.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] Rather than just learning invariance, JEPAs learn by predicting masked latent representations from visible context.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] JEPA has been applied to domains such as image analysis, audio processing, and motion in images and video.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] SSL belongs to supervised learning methods insofar as the goal is to generate a classified output from the input.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] At the same time, however, it does not require the explicit use of labeled input-output pairs.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] Instead, correlations, metadata embedded in the data, or domain knowledge present in the input are implicitly and autonomously extracted from the data.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] These supervisory signals, extracted from the data, can then be used for training.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] SSL is similar to unsupervised learning in that it does not require labels in the sample data.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] Unlike unsupervised learning, however, learning is not done using inherent data structures.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] Semi-supervised learning combines supervised and unsupervised learning, requiring only a small portion of the learning data be labeled.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] In transfer learning, a model designed for one task is reused on a different task.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] Training an autoencoder intrinsically constitutes a self-supervised process, because the output pattern needs to become an optimal reconstruction of the input pattern itself.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] However, in current jargon, the term 'self-supervised' often refers to tasks based on a pretext-task training setup.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] This involves the (human) design of such pretext task(s), unlike the case of fully self-contained autoencoder training.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] In reinforcement learning, self-supervising learning from a combination of losses can create abstract representations where only the most important information about the state are kept in a compressed way.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] Self-supervised learning is particularly suitable for speech recognition.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] For example, Facebook developed *wav2vec*, a self-supervised algorithm, to perform speech recognition using two deep convolutional neural networks that build on each other.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] Google's Bidirectional Encoder Representations from Transformers (BERT) model is used to better understand the context of search queries.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] OpenAI's GPT-3 is an autoregressive language model that can be used in language processing.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] It can be used to translate texts or answer questions, among other things.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] The Yarowsky algorithm is an example of self-supervised learning in natural language processing.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] From a small number of labeled examples, it learns to predict which word sense of a polysemous word is being used at a given point in text.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] DirectPred is a NCSSL that directly sets the predictor weights instead of learning it via typical gradient descent.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] Self-GenomeNet is an example of self-supervised learning in genomics.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] SelfAPR is an example of self-supervised learning applied to automated program repair, where a neural model is trained on perturbations of a previous version of the program under repair and uses test execution diagnostics to synthesize patches.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] Self-supervised learning continues to gain prominence as a new approach across diverse fields.
[src:few-shot-learning/contrastive-learning] Its ability to leverage unlabeled data effectively opens new possibilities for advancement in machine learning, especially in data-driven application domains.
[src:few-shot-learning/few-shot-learning] The limiting case of few-shot learning is zero-shot learning that requires no training on examples of the class to be classified; instead, the classification task must be generalized from examples of other classes.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] It can also be defined as the practice of designing and refining input instructions given to a generative AI model to produce more accurate, relevant, or useful outputs.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Effective prompt engineering involves understanding how a model interprets language, and may include techniques such as few-shot prompting, chain-of-thought prompting, and role assignment.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] It is increasingly considered a skill for working with large language models (LLMs) in both research and professional contexts.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] During the 2020s AI boom, prompt engineering became regarded as a business capability across corporations and industries.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Employees with the title **prompt engineer** were hired to create prompts that would increase productivity and efficacy, although the individual title has since lost traction amid AI models that produce better prompts than humans and corporate training in prompting for general employees.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Common prompting techniques include multi-shot, chain-of-thought, and tree-of-thought prompting, as well as assigning roles to the model.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Automated prompt generation methods, such as retrieval-augmented generation (RAG), provide for greater accuracy and a wider scope of functions for prompt engineers.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Prompt injection is a type of cybersecurity attack that targets machine learning models through malicious prompts.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] A prompt is some natural language text that describes and prescribes the task that an artificial intelligence (AI) should perform.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] A prompt for a text-to-text language model can be a query, a command, or a longer statement referencing context, instructions, and conversation history.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] The process of prompt engineering may involve designing clear queries, refining wording, providing relevant context, specifying the style of output, and assigning a character for the AI to mimic in order to guide the model toward more accurate, useful, and consistent responses.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] When communicating with a text-to-image or a text-to-audio model, a typical prompt contains a description of a desired output such as "a high-quality photo of an astronaut riding a horse" or "Lo-fi slow BPM electro chill with organic samples".
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Prompt engineering may be applied to text-to-image models to achieve a desired subject, style, layout, lighting, and aesthetic.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Common terms used to describe various specific prompt engineering techniques include *chain-of-thought*, *tree-of-thought*, and retrieval-augmented generation (RAG).
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] A 2024 survey of the field identified over 50 distinct text-based prompting techniques, 40 multimodal variants, and a vocabulary of 33 terms used across prompting research, highlighting a present lack of standardised terminology for prompt engineering.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Vibe coding is an AI-assisted software development method where a user prompts an LLM with a description of what they want and lets it generate or edit the code.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] In 2025, "vibe coding" was the Collins Dictionary word of the year.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Context engineering is a related process that focuses on the context elements that accompany user prompts, which include system instructions, retrieved knowledge, tool definitions, conversation summaries, and task metadata.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Context engineering is performed to improve reliability, provenance and token efficiency in production LLM systems.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] The concept emphasises operational practices such as token budgeting, provenance tags, versioning of context artifacts, observability (logging which context was supplied), and context regression tests to ensure that changes to supplied context do not silently alter system behaviour.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Research has found that the performance of large language models (LLMs) is highly sensitive to choices such as the ordering of examples, the quality of demonstration labels, and even small variations in phrasing.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] In some cases, reordering examples in a prompt produced accuracy shifts of more than 40 percent.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] A model's ability to temporarily learn from prompts is known as *in-context learning*.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] In-context learning is an emergent ability of large language models.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] It is an emergent property of model scale, meaning that breaks in scaling laws occur, leading to its efficacy increasing at a different rate in larger models than in smaller models.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Unlike training and fine-tuning, which produce lasting changes, in-context learning is temporary.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Training models to perform in-context learning can be viewed as a form of meta-learning, or "learning to learn".
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Research consistently demonstrates that LLMs are highly sensitive to subtle variations in prompt formatting, structure, and linguistic properties.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Some studies have shown up to 76 accuracy points across formatting changes in few-shot settings.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Linguistic features significantly influence prompt effectiveness—such as morphology, syntax, and lexico-semantic changes—which meaningfully enhance task performance across a variety of tasks.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Clausal syntax, for example, improves consistency and reduces uncertainty in knowledge retrieval.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] This sensitivity persists even with larger model sizes, additional few-shot examples, or instruction tuning.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] To address sensitivity of models and make them more robust, several evaluative methods have been proposed.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] FormatSpread facilitates systematic analysis by evaluating a range of plausible prompt formats, offering a more comprehensive performance interval.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Similarly, PromptEval estimates performance distributions across diverse prompts, enabling robust metrics such as performance quantiles and accurate evaluations under constrained budgets.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] A prompt may include a few examples for a model to learn from in-context, an implementation of few-shot learning for LLMs.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] It is possible to fine-tune models on CoT reasoning datasets to enhance this capability further and stimulate better interpretability.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] As originally proposed by Google, each CoT prompt is accompanied by a set of input/output examples—called *exemplars*—to demonstrate the desired model output, making it a few-shot prompting technique.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] However, according to a later paper from researchers at Google and the University of Tokyo, simply appending the words "Let's think step-by-step" was also effective, which allowed for CoT to be employed as a zero-shot technique.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] In 2022, text-to-image models like DALL-E 2, Stable Diffusion, and Midjourney were released to the public.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] These models take text prompts as input and use them to generate images.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Early text-to-image models typically do not understand negation, grammar and sentence structure in the same way as large language models, and may thus require a different set of prompting techniques.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] The prompt "a party with no cake" may produce an image including a cake.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] A text-to-image prompt commonly includes a description of the subject of the art, the desired medium (such as *digital painting* or *photography*), style (such as *hyperrealistic* or *pop-art*), lighting (such as *rim lighting* or *crepuscular rays*), color, and texture.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Word order also affects the output of a text-to-image prompt.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Words closer to the start of a prompt may be emphasized more heavily.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Some text-to-image models are capable of imitating the style of particular artists by name.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] For example, the phrase *in the style of Greg Rutkowski* has been used in Stable Diffusion and Midjourney prompts to generate images in the distinctive style of Polish digital artist Greg Rutkowski.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Famous artists such as Vincent van Gogh and Salvador Dalí have also been used for styling and testing.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] For text-to-image models, *textual inversion* performs an optimization process to create a new word embedding based on a set of example images.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] This embedding vector acts as a "pseudo-word" which can be included in a prompt to express the content or style of the examples.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] In 2023, Meta's AI research released Segment Anything, a computer vision model that can perform image segmentation by prompting.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] As an alternative to text prompts, Segment Anything can accept bounding boxes, segmentation masks, and foreground/background points.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] The process of writing and refining a prompt for an LLM or generative AI shares some parallels with an iterative engineering design process, such as by discovering reusable best practices through reproducible experimentation.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] However, several fundamental limitations constrain its reliability as a discipline.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Effective prompting strategies are highly model specific, a technique that improves performance on one model may degrade it on another, making generalization difficult.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Prompts are also brittle: minor surface-level changes in phrasing, punctuation, or word order can produce dramatically different outputs, even when the semantic intent remains identical.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] This instability makes it difficult to establish durable, transferable prompt patterns across deployment contexts.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Furthermore, as AI models continue to improve in their ability to interpret user intent directly, many manual prompting techniques are becoming obsolete.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Advances in instruction-following and model reasoning have reduced the marginal value of elaborate prompt construction for everyday tasks, raising questions about the long-term viability of prompt engineering as a standalone discipline.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Recent research has explored automated prompt engineering, using optimization algorithms to generate or refine prompts without human intervention.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] These automated approaches aim to identify effective prompt patterns by analyzing model gradients, reinforcement feedback, or evolutionary processes, reducing the need for manual experimentation.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Retrieval-augmented generation is a technique that enables GenAI models to retrieve and incorporate new information.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] It modifies interactions with an LLM so that the model responds to user queries with reference to a specified set of documents, using this information to supplement information from its pre-existing training data.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] This allows LLMs to use domain-specific and/or updated information.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] RAG improves large language models by incorporating information retrieval before generating responses.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Unlike traditional LLMs that rely on static training data, RAG pulls relevant text from databases, uploaded documents, or web sources.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] By dynamically retrieving information, RAG enables AI to generate more accurate responses and fewer AI hallucinations without frequent retraining.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] GraphRAG (coined by Microsoft Research) is a technique that extends RAG with the use of a knowledge graph to allow the model to connect disparate pieces of information, synthesize insights, and understand summarized semantic concepts over large data collections.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] It was shown to be effective on datasets like the Violent Incident Information from News Articles.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] LLMs themselves can be used to compose prompts for LLMs.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] CoT examples can be generated by LLM themselves.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] In "auto-CoT", a library of questions are converted to vectors by a model such as BERT.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Questions close to the centroid of each cluster are selected, in order to have a subset of diverse questions.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] An LLM does zero-shot CoT on each selected question.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] The question and the corresponding CoT answer are added to a dataset of demonstrations.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] These diverse demonstrations can then added to prompts for few-shot learning.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] In "prefix-tuning", "prompt tuning", or "soft prompting", floating-point vectors are searched directly by gradient descent to maximize the log-likelihood on outputs.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] An earlier result uses the same idea of gradient descent search, but is designed for masked language models like BERT, and searches only over token sequences, rather than numerical vectors.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Formally, it searches for $\arg \max _{\tilde {X}}\sum _{i}\log Pr[Y^{i}|{\tilde {X}}\ast X^{i}]$ where ${\tilde {X}}$ ranges over token sequences of a specified length.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Early precedents of structured user interaction with ruled-based AI systems can be found in enterprise automation software from 1990s.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] For example, The Intelligent Filling Manager (1999), developed by Krishna C.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Mukherjee, used a dynamic Q&A interface driven by rule-based expert system to collect user inputs for generating regulatory filings automatically across jurisdictions.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] While not involving neural networks, such systems featured prompt-like workflows that influenced later human-in-the-loop AI designs.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] In 2018, researchers first proposed that all previously separate tasks in natural language processing (NLP) could be cast as question-answer problems over a context.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] The AI boom saw an increased focus within academic literature and professional practice on applying prompting techniques to get the model to output the desired outcome and avoid nonsensical output, a process characterized by trial-and-error.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] According to *The Wall Street Journal* in 2025, the job of prompt engineer was one of the hottest in 2023, but has become obsolete due to models that better intuit user intent and to company trainings.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] A repository for prompts reported that over 2,000 public prompts for around 170 datasets were available in February 2022.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] In 2022, the *chain-of-thought* prompting technique was proposed by Google researchers.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] In 2023, several text-to-text and text-to-image prompt databases were made publicly available.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] The Personalized Image-Prompt (PIP) dataset, a generated image-text dataset that has been categorized by 3,115 users, has also been made available publicly in 2024.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Prompt injection is a cybersecurity exploit in which adversaries craft inputs that appear legitimate but are designed to cause unintended behavior in machine learning models, particularly large language models.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] This attack takes advantage of the model's inability to distinguish between developer-defined prompts and user inputs, allowing adversaries to bypass safeguards and influence model behaviour.
[src:few-shot-learning/in-context-learning] While LLMs are designed to follow trusted instructions, they can be manipulated into carrying out unintended responses through carefully crafted inputs.
[src:few-shot-learning/statistical-classification] When classification is performed by a computer, statistical methods are normally used to develop the algorithm.
[src:few-shot-learning/statistical-classification] Often, the individual observations are analyzed into a set of quantifiable properties, known variously as explanatory variables or *features*.
[src:few-shot-learning/statistical-classification] These properties may variously be categorical (e.g.
[src:few-shot-learning/statistical-classification] "large", "medium" or "small"), integer-valued (e.g. the number of occurrences of a particular word in an email) or real-valued (e.g. a measurement of blood pressure).
[src:few-shot-learning/statistical-classification] Other classifiers work by comparing observations to previous observations by means of a similarity or distance function.
[src:few-shot-learning/statistical-classification] An algorithm that implements classification, especially in a concrete implementation, is known as a **classifier**.
[src:few-shot-learning/statistical-classification] The term "classifier" sometimes also refers to the mathematical function, implemented by a classification algorithm, that maps input data to a category.
[src:few-shot-learning/statistical-classification] Terminology across fields is quite varied.
[src:few-shot-learning/statistical-classification] In machine learning, the observations are often known as *instances*, the explanatory variables are termed *features* (grouped into a feature vector), and the possible categories to be predicted are *classes*.
[src:few-shot-learning/statistical-classification] Other fields may use different terminology: e.g. in community ecology, the term "classification" normally refers to cluster analysis.
[src:few-shot-learning/statistical-classification] Classification and clustering are examples of the more general problem of pattern recognition, which is the assignment of some sort of output value to a given input value.
[src:few-shot-learning/statistical-classification] A common subclass of classification is probabilistic classification.
[src:few-shot-learning/statistical-classification] Algorithms of this nature use statistical inference to find the best class for a given instance.
[src:few-shot-learning/statistical-classification] Unlike other algorithms, which simply output a "best" class, probabilistic algorithms output a probability of the instance being a member of each of the possible classes.
[src:few-shot-learning/statistical-classification] The best class is normally then selected as the one with the highest probability.
[src:few-shot-learning/statistical-classification] Early work on statistical classification was undertaken by Fisher, in the context of two-group problems, leading to Fisher's linear discriminant function as the rule for assigning a group to a new observation.
[src:few-shot-learning/statistical-classification] This early work assumed that data-values within each of the two groups had a multivariate normal distribution.
[src:few-shot-learning/statistical-classification] The extension of this same context to more than two groups has also been considered with a restriction imposed that the classification rule should be linear.
[src:few-shot-learning/statistical-classification] Unlike frequentist procedures, Bayesian classification procedures provide a natural way of taking into account any available information about the relative sizes of the different groups within the overall population.
[src:few-shot-learning/statistical-classification] Bayesian procedures tend to be computationally expensive and, in the days before Markov chain Monte Carlo computations were developed, approximations for Bayesian clustering rules were devised.
[src:few-shot-learning/statistical-classification] Some Bayesian procedures involve the calculation of group-membership probabilities: these provide a more informative outcome than a simple attribution of a single group-label to each new observation.
[src:few-shot-learning/statistical-classification] Classification can be thought of as two separate problems – binary classification and multiclass classification.
[src:few-shot-learning/statistical-classification] In binary classification, a better understood task, only two classes are involved, whereas multiclass classification involves assigning an object to one of several classes.
[src:few-shot-learning/statistical-classification] Since many classification methods have been developed specifically for binary classification, multiclass classification often requires the combined use of multiple binary classifiers.
[src:few-shot-learning/statistical-classification] Most algorithms describe an individual instance whose category is to be predicted using a feature vector of individual, measurable properties of the instance.
[src:few-shot-learning/statistical-classification] Each property is termed a feature, also known in statistics as an explanatory variable (or independent variable, although features may or may not be statistically independent).
[src:few-shot-learning/statistical-classification] "large", "medium" or "small"); integer-valued (e.g. the number of occurrences of a particular word in an email); or real-valued (e.g. a measurement of blood pressure).
[src:few-shot-learning/statistical-classification] If the instance is an image, the feature values might correspond to the pixels of an image; if the instance is a piece of text, the feature values might be occurrence frequencies of different words.
[src:few-shot-learning/statistical-classification] Some algorithms work only in terms of discrete data and require that real-valued or integer-valued data be *discretized* into groups (e.g. less than 5, between 5 and 10, or greater than 10).
[src:few-shot-learning/statistical-classification] A large number of algorithms for classification can be phrased in terms of a linear function that assigns a score to each possible category *k* by combining the feature vector of an instance with a vector of weights, using a dot product.
[src:few-shot-learning/statistical-classification] The predicted category is the one with the highest score.
[src:few-shot-learning/statistical-classification] In discrete choice theory, where instances represent people and categories represent choices, the score is considered the utility associated with person *i* choosing category *k*.
[src:few-shot-learning/statistical-classification] Algorithms with this basic setup are known as linear classifiers.
[src:few-shot-learning/statistical-classification] What distinguishes them is the procedure for determining (training) the optimal weights/coefficients and the way that the score is interpreted.
[src:few-shot-learning/statistical-classification] Since no single form of classification is appropriate for all data sets, a large toolkit of classification algorithms has been developed.
[src:few-shot-learning/statistical-classification] Choices between different possible algorithms are frequently made on the basis of quantitative evaluation of accuracy.
[src:few-shot-learning/statistical-classification] In some of these, it is employed as a data mining procedure, while in others more detailed statistical modeling is undertaken.
[src:few-shot-learning/transfer-learning] Since transfer learning makes use of training with multiple objective functions it is related to cost-sensitive machine learning and multi-objective optimization.
[src:few-shot-learning/transfer-learning] In 1976, Bozinovski and Fulgosi published a paper addressing transfer learning in neural network training.
[src:few-shot-learning/transfer-learning] The paper gives a mathematical and geometrical model of the topic.
[src:few-shot-learning/transfer-learning] In 1981, a report considered the application of transfer learning to a dataset of images representing letters of computer terminals, experimentally demonstrating positive and negative transfer learning.
[src:few-shot-learning/transfer-learning] In 1992, Lorien Pratt formulated the discriminability-based transfer (DBT) algorithm.
[src:few-shot-learning/transfer-learning] By 1998, the field had advanced to include multi-task learning, along with more formal theoretical foundations.
[src:few-shot-learning/transfer-learning] Influential publications on transfer learning include the book *Learning to Learn* in 1998, a 2009 survey and a 2019 survey.
[src:few-shot-learning/transfer-learning] Ng said in his NIPS 2016 tutorial that TL would become the next driver of machine learning commercial success after supervised learning.
[src:few-shot-learning/transfer-learning] In the 2020 paper, "Rethinking Pre-Training and self-training", Zoph et al. reported that pre-training can hurt accuracy, and advocate self-training instead.
[src:few-shot-learning/transfer-learning] The definition of transfer learning is given in terms of domains and tasks.
[src:few-shot-learning/transfer-learning] A domain ${\mathcal {D}}$ consists of: a feature space ${\mathcal {X}}$ and a marginal probability distribution $P(X)$ , where $X=\{x_{1},...,x_{n}\}\in {\mathcal {X}}$ .
[src:few-shot-learning/transfer-learning] Given a specific domain, ${\mathcal {D}}=\{{\mathcal {X}},P(X)\}$ , a task consists of two components: a label space ${\mathcal {Y}}$ and an objective predictive function $f:{\mathcal {X}}\rightarrow {\mathcal {Y}}$ .
[src:few-shot-learning/transfer-learning] The function f is used to predict the corresponding label $f(x)$ of a new instance x .
[src:few-shot-learning/transfer-learning] Algorithms for transfer learning are available in Markov logic networks and Bayesian networks.
[src:few-shot-learning/transfer-learning] Transfer learning has been applied to cancer subtype discovery, building utilization, general game playing, text classification, digit recognition, medical imaging and spam filtering.
[src:few-shot-learning/transfer-learning] It was noted that this relationship worked in both directions, showing that EEG brainwaves can likewise be used to classify EMG signals.
[src:few-shot-learning/transfer-learning] The experiments noted that the accuracy of neural networks and convolutional neural networks were improved through transfer learning both prior to any learning (compared to standard random weight distribution) and at the end of the learning process (asymptote).
[src:few-shot-learning/transfer-learning] That is, results are improved by exposure to another domain.
[src:few-shot-learning/transfer-learning] Moreover, the end-user of a pre-trained model can change the structure of fully-connected layers to improve performance.
